---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const meta = {
  title: 'Webflow vs WordPress 2025: No-Code vs Open Source',
  description: 'Webflow vs WordPress: Webflow ($16-212/month) is visual no-code with clean code export. WordPress (free self-hosted, ~$60-500/year hosted) is open-source with unlimited plugins. Webflow: easier, faster build, limited. WordPress: unlimited flexibility, steeper learning curve, maintenance burden. Choose Webflow for design. Choose WordPress for functionality.',
  image: '/og-image.svg',
  keywords: ['Webflow vs WordPress', 'no-code vs CMS', 'website builder comparison', 'Webflow review', 'WordPress review'],
};
---

<Layout {...meta}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#4353FF]/5 to-[#21759B]/5 py-12 sm:py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <p class="text-[10px] sm:text-xs font-black text-[#4353FF] mb-4 tracking-[0.3em] uppercase">
        Website Builder Comparison · 2025
      </p>

      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-black mb-6 leading-tight">
        Webflow vs WordPress
      </h1>

      <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
        Webflow and WordPress represent two completely different philosophies. Webflow is modern no-code: visual design, clean output, limited but polished. WordPress is open-source legacy: unlimited plugins, steep learning curve, maintenance burden. Webflow costs more but works out of the box. WordPress is free to start but costs time and technical knowledge. Both can build excellent sites. The choice depends on your priorities.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-white bg-opacity-50 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-6">
        <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">
          Quick answer: Choose Webflow if you want visual design control without coding and don't mind paying. Choose WordPress if you need unlimited functionality, are willing to learn, or want the cheapest long-term option. Webflow is faster to build. WordPress can do anything but takes longer.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Quick Comparison -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Quick Comparison
    </h2>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-100">
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-bold">Feature</th>
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-bold">Webflow</th>
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-bold">WordPress</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Ease of Use</td>
            <td class="p-4">Visual, intuitive after learning</td>
            <td class="p-4">Dashboard-based, steeper curve</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Flexibility</td>
            <td class="p-4">Limited but powerful within scope</td>
            <td class="p-4">Unlimited via plugins</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Learning Curve</td>
            <td class="p-4">2-4 weeks to become proficient</td>
            <td class="p-4">Ongoing, never truly ends</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Maintenance</td>
            <td class="p-4">Webflow handles everything</td>
            <td class="p-4">You handle updates, security, backups</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Cost (First Year)</td>
            <td class="p-4">$192-2,544/year</td>
            <td class="p-4">$0-500/year (varies widely)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Cost (Long-term)</td>
            <td class="p-4">Price increases with scale</td>
            <td class="p-4">Cheaper if self-managed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Best For</td>
            <td class="p-4">Designers, marketing sites</td>
            <td class="p-4">Complex functionality, content sites</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Webflow Deep Dive -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      What Webflow Does Well
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Visual Design Without Code</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Design visually, get clean HTML/CSS/JS output.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> You see what you're building. No preview-refresh dance. No "that's not what I designed" handoff gaps. Visual control rivals coding but faster. WordPress requires page builders (Elementor, Divi) to approach this, and they generate bloated code.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Zero Maintenance</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Webflow handles hosting, security, updates, backups.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> WordPress requires constant maintenance. Plugin conflicts, theme updates, security patches, backup management. It never ends. Webflow: you build, you publish, you're done. Platform team handles everything else.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Clean Code Export</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Export actual production-ready code when needed.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> You're not locked in. Need to migrate? Export the code. Hand off to developers? They'll respect the output. WordPress generates messy code. Page builders add div soup. Webflow code is semantic and organized.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Built-in CMS for Dynamic Content</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Collection-based CMS included in CMS plan.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> WordPress has CMS built in obviously. But Webflow's CMS is intuitive and visual. Custom content types, relationships, filtering, referencing. Create blogs, portfolios, product catalogs without touching code.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Hosted Performance</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Fast loading out of the box without optimization plugins.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> WordPress speed requires work: caching plugins, image optimization, CDN setup, database cleanup. Webflow sites load fast automatically. AWS hosting, automatic optimization, built-in CDN.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WordPress Deep Dive -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      What WordPress Does Well
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Unlimited Plugin Ecosystem</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">60,000+ plugins for everything imaginable.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Need a specific feature? There's probably a plugin. E-commerce, memberships, forums, directories, bookings, galleries, forms. Webflow can't do most of this without custom development. WordPress: install plugin, done.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">True Content Management Power</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">WordPress was built for publishing. It shows.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Categories, tags, custom taxonomies, user roles, editorial workflows, revision history, scheduling. Webflow's CMS is good. WordPress CMS is mature and battle-tested by publishers worldwide.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">E-commerce Maturity</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">WooCommerce powers 40% of online stores for a reason.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Webflow e-commerce exists but is basic. WooCommerce is full-featured: subscriptions, bookings, product bundles, dynamic pricing, hundreds of extensions. If you're serious about selling, WordPress + WooCommerce beats Webflow.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Cheaper Long-term (Self-hosted)</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Pay for hosting only. Software is free forever.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Webflow costs increase forever. WordPress: buy a domain, pay $5-20/month for hosting, you're set. Premium themes and plugins cost money but are one-time purchases or annual fees far less than Webflow subscription.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Massive Community and Resources</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Largest ecosystem in web development.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Stuck? Search online. Thousands of tutorials, forums, YouTube videos, developers. Webflow's community is growing but tiny compared to WordPress. If you need help, WordPress has answers everywhere.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Trade-offs -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      The Real Trade-offs
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-yellow-50 border-2 border-yellow-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Webflow: Freedom Within Constraints</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">You can design anything visually. But functionality is limited.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The constraint:</strong> What Webflow supports, you can do beautifully. What it doesn't, you're stuck. Need complex custom functionality? You'll need external tools or custom development. Webflow is a walled garden with very nice walls.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-yellow-50 border-2 border-yellow-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">WordPress: Unlimited Flexibility, Unlimited Complexity</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">You can build anything. But everything breaks eventually.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The complexity:</strong> Plugin conflicts, theme updates breaking layouts, PHP version compatibility, security vulnerabilities. WordPress is freedom but also responsibility. Things will break. You'll fix them. Forever.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-yellow-50 border-2 border-yellow-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Webflow: Higher Cost, Lower Headaches</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Pay more, worry less.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The math:</strong> Webflow CMS plan = $432/year. WordPress self-hosted = ~$120/year hosting + maybe $100/year plugins = $220/year. Webflow costs ~2x more. But you save hours of maintenance. Is your time worth $200/year? Probably.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-yellow-50 border-2 border-yellow-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">WordPress: Lower Cost, Higher Learning Curve</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Pay less, learn more.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The investment:</strong> WordPress learning curve never ends. New plugins, updates, security practices, performance optimization. You're always learning something new. Great if you enjoy it. Draining if you don't.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- When to Choose -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      When to Choose Each
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">✅ Choose Webflow If</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>You're a designer:</strong> Visual control matters more than custom functionality</li>
          <li>• <strong>You build marketing sites:</strong> SaaS landing pages, portfolios, agency sites</li>
          <li>• <strong>You hate maintenance:</strong> Don't want to deal with updates, security, backups</li>
          <li>• <strong>Budget allows for subscriptions:</strong> You can pay $36-212/month indefinitely</li>
          <li>• <strong>You need clean code export:</strong> Want the option to migrate or hand off</li>
          <li>• <strong>You're building simpler sites:</strong> No complex functionality needed</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">✅ Choose WordPress If</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>You need complex functionality:</strong> E-commerce, memberships, forums, directories</li>
          <li>• <strong>You're building a content site:</strong> Blog, publication, news site with complex taxonomy</li>
          <li>• <strong>Budget is tight:</strong> Want cheapest long-term option</li>
          <li>• <strong>You don't mind learning:</strong> Willing to invest time in technical skills</li>
          <li>• <strong>You want plugin flexibility:</strong> Need features Webflow can't do</li>
          <li>• <strong>You're a developer:</strong> Comfortable with PHP, hosting, maintenance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Bottom Line -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <div class="bg-white bg-opacity-50 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black mb-6">Bottom Line</h2>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">Webflow and WordPress both work. Webflow is modern no-code with beautiful constraints. WordPress is open-source with unlimited complexity. Webflow costs more but works forever. WordPress costs less but requires constant attention.</p>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6"><strong>Choose Webflow for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <li>• Visual design without coding</li>
        <li>• Marketing sites and portfolios</li>
        <li>• Zero maintenance lifestyle</li>
        <li>• Faster build process</li>
        <li>• Clean code and export options</li>
        <li>• Simpler functionality requirements</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6"><strong>Choose WordPress for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <li>• Unlimited plugin functionality</li>
        <li>• Complex content architectures</li>
        <li>• Serious e-commerce needs</li>
        <li>• Cheapest long-term option</li>
        <li>• Massive community support</li>
        <li>• Full control and flexibility</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700"><strong>The honest truth:</strong> If you're a designer building marketing sites, Webflow will make you happier. If you're building complex functionality or running a content operation, WordPress is the only viable choice. If you're a business trying to decide: hire a Webflow designer for marketing sites, hire a WordPress developer for everything else. Both tools are excellent at what they do. Neither is universally better.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-6 text-gray-900">
      Related Comparisons
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <a href="/webflow-review" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Webflow Review</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Full Webflow review</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/framer-vs-squarespace" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Framer vs Squarespace</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Modern vs established</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
